            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the Morse code translator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool implements the official ITU International Morse code
                table and standard timing rules. It can encode plain text into
                Morse code and decode Morse back into readable text.
              </p>
              <p>
                Each character is mapped to a sequence of dots (<code>.</code>)
                and dashes (<code>-</code>). When you type in the input box, the
                translator updates the output in real time.
              </p>

              <h3>Timing and speed (WPM)</h3>
              <p>
                Morse timing is based on a basic time unit: the dot length. All
                other durations are multiples of this unit:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Dot: 1 unit</li>
                <li>Dash: 3 units</li>
                <li>Gap between symbols in a letter: 1 unit</li>
                <li>Gap between letters: 3 units</li>
                <li>Gap between words: 7 units</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The dot duration in milliseconds is computed from the selected
                speed in words per minute (WPM) using the standard PARIS model:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box mono text-sm">
                dotLengthMs = 1200 / WPM
              </div>
              <p>
                For example, at 20 WPM the dot length is 60 ms, a dash is 180
                ms, and the gap between words is 420 ms.
              </p>

              <h3>Encoding rules (Text → Morse)</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>Convert the input to uppercase for matching.</li>
                <li>
                  For each character, look up its Morse sequence in the table.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Join symbols in a letter without extra spaces (e.g.
                  <code>A → .-</code>).
                </li>
                <li>Separate letters with a single space.</li>
                <li>
                  Separate words with <code>/</code> (slash) or 3 spaces in the
                  encoded output.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Decoding rules (Morse → Text)</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Normalize the input by replacing multiple spaces with a single
                  space.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Split the Morse stream into words using <code>/</code> or 3+
                  spaces.
                </li>
                <li>Split each word into letters by single spaces.</li>
                <li>
                  For each Morse sequence, look up the corresponding character.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If a sequence is unknown, a placeholder <code>□</code> is
                  used.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Common use cases</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Learning Morse code for ham radio exams.</li>
                <li>Creating secret messages for games or puzzles.</li>
                <li>
                  Practicing listening skills with adjustable speed and tone.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Generating Morse for educational videos or classroom demos.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Can I paste noisy Morse with extra spaces or line breaks?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The decoder ignores extra whitespace and line breaks. Just
                make sure dots and dashes are preserved.
              </p>

              <h3>What about non‑Latin characters?</h3>
              <p>
                Where standard Morse exists (for example, <code>Ä</code>,
                <code>Ñ</code>, <code>Ö</code>, <code>Ü</code>), they are
                supported. Other characters are skipped or replaced with a
                placeholder.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this work offline?</h3>
              <p>
                The translation logic runs entirely in your browser. Once the
                page is loaded, encoding and decoding do not require a network
                connection, but audio playback still depends on your device’s
                audio capabilities.
              </p>
            </section>
